 {"id":"coding_agent_session_search-4f6","title":"Remote Sources & Provenance Epic","description":"# Remote Sources & Provenance System

## Vision
Enable cass to ingest, search, and display agent conversation history from multiple machines, making it the canonical "agent history search layer" for multi-machine workflows.

## Problem Statement
Developers work across multiple machines (laptop, desktop, cloud dev environments). Agent history is currently siloed per machine:
- Solutions discovered on work laptop are invisible when searching from home desktop
- No cross-machine knowledge discovery
- CMS and other tools need a unified search layer

## Core Capabilities
1. **Remote session ingestion** via SSH using existing SSH configs/keys
2. **First-class provenance metadata** (source_id, origin_kind, origin_host) stored as queryable fields
3. **Filtering** by source/origin in CLI, TUI, and robot outputs
4. **Visual distinction** for remote-origin records (darker shade + badge)

## Architecture Decisions

### Mirror vs Direct Query
Chosen: Local mirroring. Rationale:
- cass view needs local file access for source context
- Offline access is valuable
- Search performance depends on local index
- Incremental sync more efficient than per-query fetches

### Provenance as First-Class Fields
Not just metadata_json - enables:
- Efficient Tantivy filtering
- Clean CLI/robot output
- Type-safe code handling

### Workspace Path Rewriting
Enables cross-machine workspace filtering:
- /home/user/projects → /Users/user/projects mapping
- Makes workspace filters meaningful across machines

## Success Criteria
- [ ] Can add SSH source and sync logs from remote machine
- [ ] Search results show provenance (source_id, host)
- [ ] CLI --source filter works correctly
- [ ] TUI shows visual distinction for remote results
- [ ] Robot output includes provenance fields
- [ ] No identity collisions across sources
- [ ] Existing users can upgrade without data loss

